At the end of every year, I like to go through all the photos, and just enjoy every day. This year is different, and here's why.
9 years ago, Future Shop let me go. They were rebranding to Best Buy, and I found myself without a job. I had enough money to make it a year, so I decided to give full time photography a go. If it didn't work out, I'd go work as a cashier. As long as I have a job where I'm around people, I'm happy.
Okanagan, you made this dream I hadn't even dare to dream a reality. 
Within a month of putting up my website, I had booked a full 20 weddings, and dozens of family photos. I kept on expecting it to slow down or stop, but it's gotten crazier.
Now, in my 9th year of being a full time photographer, we've danced on frozen lakes. We took out the dad jokes, I've photographed your boy hugging you because he's only 7 once.
We ran off during your reception to get some sunset photos. 
I've watched you propose, your father cry as he leads you down the aisle, then we all froze together as the snow fell - looking for that perfect shot.  I took photos of you on your 30th birthday, ordered in some red smoke bombs, and gave your kid one. You stood out in the most incredible sun, 8 months pregnant, proud as only a mother can be. You found me after you found your grad dress, and we took photos, and this year 8 years later, I photographed your wedding and met your husband.
This year left me speechless. 
Thank you everyone for supporting a local artist. I'll keep doing this for as long as you keep asking me to.

A lot of what makes a shoot amazing is the work before (scouting out, coming out with a solid plan, getting a good idea of expectations, 50 emails), and after (normally around 60 hours of editing, the sneak peek, a video if requested, oh and more edits, and sometimes a phone call with grandma helping her download her photos to her iPhone 3gs)

But it's all worth it, of course. You look at your image, how it interacts with your space, the space it creates in your mind. There's nothing else like it.

There's a few things thats just love about the album. They really stand out. 
First is the daddy-daughter first look. I might look like I was close, but I actually really far away. You have to let the moment unfold on its own, and to do that, you can't interfere. I wasn't a foot away, in their faces, I was like ten feet away. 
This is also my issue with too big of a team - if you'd like a videographer, sure. Do it. But don't have your photographer, second shooter, videographer, and two assistants there. You'll never get moments like this. It won't happen. 
It also helps to let us know what your priority is. If it's video, I'll let the videographer do his thing. If it's photos, I'm kicking everyone else out except for the videographer.

Second, did you see the ceremony? They were both so in the moment. I'll remember it always. 

Third, the formals. They were so incredible - we went to the old abandoned church from the 1920's. You can see the roof is a bit caved in. Imagine that! Focus was on laid back, fun photos, candid style, fun. And that's exactly what we got with such an amazing crew. 

I hope you all enjoy. Special thanks to Durali Villa.

Brides and wedding photographers, take note. This is going to be a long entry. 

2 years ago, I photographed a wedding at Fairmont Banff Springs. There's a few things that I learned, a few small things that made this wedding really stand out in my mind.

First off, the feeling. Choose your bridal party carefully! This group brought on the party - there was never a dull moment, everyone was cracking jokes, no one complained about the cold. I've given pep talks before, but honestly this group brought such an unreal energy of excitement to the day - it was certainly a highlight. Most wedding photographers know exactly what I'm talking about - when there's so much joy in the day that you just can't stop beaming. This doesn't happen by accident. It's a distinct, purposeful decision that every person in these photos made. And it made a difference. Such a wonderful difference.

Next, I scouted carefully. After 6 hours of scouting the day before, I had more than enough spots in mind. Reading google reviews is one thing, but I made it a point to talk to the hotel staff, the staff at the coffee shop, then a group of college kids at the coffee shop, and just about everyone else who would talk to me. Then I found a first look spot, just by talking to a janitor. He said, "We have a giant ballroom that hasn't been in use for years. Come check it out." And I did, and messaged the bride "We have a new spot. For the first look."

This lens is a pain.

When it comes to photography, the question of whether it should be bright or dark is a complex one. Even for the same couple, on the same day, a photo can be either bright and moody, or dark and traditional. Depending on the season, couples may comment on how bright or dark the photos are. For instance, in the summer, people might say "Your photos are so bright!" while in the fall, they might say "Your photos are so dark!"

Different strokes for different folks, as they say. The time of day and season can also impact the contrast and color of the photos. A 3 pm ceremony in winter, for example, might produce high-contrast images with the white of the wedding dress standing out against the blue of the milky way or falling snow. On the other hand, a noon ceremony in the summer could create photos with a white dress standing out against bright green grass and blossoming cherry trees.

As a photographer, my style tends to lean towards vivid colors. I don't like artificially lightened or darkened colors, and I want the colors to pop. I want you to see the pinks, the deep greens, and the faded oranges of a sunset, as you remember it. My goal is to create classic photos that stand the test of time. Creating a captivating black-and-white photograph involves a thoughtful process. It's important to note that the absence of color alone doesn't automatically categorize a photo as "good" or "artsy."

Instead, black-and-white photography has the power to introduce a sense of drama and simplicity. This becomes particularly evident when dealing with challenging color harmonies during the editing process. Those familiar with color editing can appreciate the struggle of making colors cooperate harmoniously.

A well-crafted photograph serves as a placeholder, capable of transporting you to a specific moment, such as your wedding day. However, it's crucial to recognize that the photo itself is not the destination but rather a pathway to it.

In this particular instance, the complexity of colors in a composition proved overwhelming. To address this, I decided to strip away the colors, leaving a subtle blue tint. This choice was influenced by the "blue hour" ambiance, as the photo was taken just after the sun had set.
